# 33_layers_scriptable_smoke — first row-bound model Scriptable
# end-to-end (s216 m1 + m2 + m3), rewritten in s217 m1 to use the
# new `set <name> to result` variable grammar. Renamed from slot 26
# in s229 m1 to break the dual-test-slot collision with
# 26_scripter_singletons.curvzs.
#
# Validates the design banked in CANON's "Row-bound model Scriptables —
# collection-as-router with transient per-instance proxies" entry.
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   layers         — collection. ONE registry entry. Set verbs, set
#                    queries, name lookup, iid enumeration.
#   layers.<iid>   — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                    materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                    statement. Element verbs, element queries.
#
# The shared `layers` prefix is load-bearing: the router splits a
# dotted token on the first `.`, looks the prefix up in the registry,
# and asks the matched object to resolve the suffix. Collection name
# and proxy prefix MUST be the same string. m3 corrected the smoke
# test (had used `layer.<iid>` singular, which missed the `layers`
# entry and threw 'unknown object' on every per-instance address).
#
# This script owns its conditions. As long as Curvz is running with at
# least one project + one document open (the Scriptable surface can't
# create those yet — that's 5b headless-verb territory), the script
# builds up its own test world, validates it, and tears it back down
# to the exact state it found.
#
# ── Test-isolation strategy ────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every layer this script creates is renamed to a "smoke_test_*" prefix
# immediately after creation. Existing user layers (whatever was in the
# doc when the script started) are NEVER touched: not toggled, not
# renamed, not deleted. The teardown step at the bottom deletes every
# smoke_test_* layer by bound variable, leaving the user's original
# state pristine.
#
# That isolation works even if the user already had layers named
# "Layer 1", "Layer 2", etc. — we never address by those generic names,
# only by the iids of layers we created.
#
# ── Substitution grammar (s216 m2 / s217 m1) ───────────────────────────────
#
# The listener has two kinds of substitution. Both happen text-level,
# pre-tokenise, outside quoted strings, bounded by start/whitespace/`.`:
#
#   result      — the value of the last `=` line. Single-shot; every
#                 `get` and every non-Null `invoke` overwrites it.
#                 Lines emitting `ok` / `PASS` / `FAIL` / `error`
#                 leave it alone.
#   <var>       — anything bound earlier via `set <var> to result`.
#                 The slot's value at bind time is captured into the
#                 variable; subsequent lines can address `<var>` as a
#                 substitution token forever after, or until reset().
#
# Variables let this script bind each layer's iid ONCE and reference
# it by name through the rest of the run — no more `find_by_name`
# wallpaper between every per-instance line. Compare git history for
# the pre-s217 m1 version: ~40 lines of build-up wallpaper collapses
# to three `set` calls.
#
# ── Phases ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. BUILD UP  — create three smoke_test_* layers, bind each iid to
#                  a variable (a / b / c) via `set <var> to result`.
#   2. VALIDATE  — exercise collection queries and per-instance
#                  verbs/queries using the bound variables.
#   3. TEAR DOWN — delete every smoke_test_* layer; verify cleanup.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP ===
#[sub] Create three test layers. After each `new` the slot holds the
#[sub] iid; `set X to result` binds it into a variable that survives
#[sub] across every subsequent line. Rename happens via the bound
#[sub] variable, not via the slot — so the variable binding is what
#[sub] makes per-layer addressing durable.

layers new
set a to result
layers.a rename "smoke_test_a"
assert layers.a name == "smoke_test_a"

layers new
set b to result
layers.b rename "smoke_test_b"
assert layers.b name == "smoke_test_b"

layers new
set c to result
layers.c rename "smoke_test_c"
assert layers.c name == "smoke_test_c"

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE ===
#[sub] Three test layers exist, bound to variables `a`, `b`, `c`.
#[sub] Exercise the per-instance surface through `layers.<var> <verb>`
#[sub] without `find_by_name` wallpaper.

#[sub] Element queries: name, visible (default true), locked (default
#[sub] false), opacity (default 1.0), child_count (default 0), iid.

assert layers.a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert layers.a visible == true
assert layers.a locked == false
assert layers.a opacity == 1.0
assert layers.a child_count == 0
get layers.a iid

#[sub] toggle_visible round-trip — the headline element verb.

assert layers.b visible == true
layers.b toggle_visible
assert layers.b visible == false
layers.b toggle_visible
assert layers.b visible == true

#[sub] set_visible with explicit bool args.

layers.c set_visible false
assert layers.c visible == false
layers.c set_visible true
assert layers.c visible == true

#[sub] toggle_locked / set_locked.

assert layers.a locked == false
layers.a toggle_locked
assert layers.a locked == true
layers.a set_locked false
assert layers.a locked == false

#[sub] color — write a hex string, read it back. (s217 m2 renamed
#[sub] this verb from `set_color`; the old name is tested below as
#[sub] a deprecated alias.)

layers.b color "#ff8800"
assert layers.b color == "#ff8800"
layers.b color ""
assert layers.b color == ""

#[sub] opacity — note: no undo today (EditLayerFieldCommand's
#[sub] Field enum doesn't include Opacity). Round-trip on the model.
#[sub] (s217 m2 renamed this verb from `set_opacity`; the old name
#[sub] is tested below as a deprecated alias.)

layers.c opacity 0.5
assert layers.c opacity == 0.5
layers.c opacity 1.0
assert layers.c opacity == 1.0

#[sub] rename via the proxy — the variable's value is the iid, not
#[sub] the name, so renaming the layer doesn't invalidate the
#[sub] variable binding. `layers.a` keeps resolving to the same iid
#[sub] regardless of what the layer is currently called. That's the
#[sub] design payoff: variables outlast renames.

layers.a rename "smoke_test_a_renamed"
assert layers.a name == "smoke_test_a_renamed"
layers.a rename "smoke_test_a"
assert layers.a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] activate — promote each test layer to active in turn,
#[sub] verify via the collection's active_iid query. We capture the
#[sub] active_iid into a separate variable each time so we can
#[sub] cross-reference without slot interference. The `layers.active_a`
#[sub] form resolves through the same proxy router — the substitution
#[sub] is text-level, so the iid in `active_a` slots cleanly into the
#[sub] `layers.<iid>` address shape. (s217 m2 renamed this verb from
#[sub] `make_active`; the old name is tested below as a deprecated
#[sub] alias.)

layers.a activate
get layers active_iid
set active_a to result
assert layers.active_a name == "smoke_test_a"

layers.b activate
get layers active_iid
set active_b to result
assert layers.active_b name == "smoke_test_b"

layers.c activate
get layers active_iid
set active_c to result
assert layers.active_c name == "smoke_test_c"

#[sub] hide_others — set verb. Hides every other real layer; the
#[sub] target stays visible. We can't easily assert "every other layer
#[sub] is now hidden" without iteration (no foreach yet), but we can
#[sub] verify the TARGET stayed visible and the bound peers flipped.
#[sub]
#[sub] CAVEAT — TRANSIENT TOUCH OF USER LAYERS: hide_others operates
#[sub] on every real layer (Type::Layer), not just the test layers.
#[sub] During this section the user's existing layers ALSO flip to
#[sub] hidden, then back to visible when show_all runs below. The
#[sub] net state change is zero (visibility is restored), but the
#[sub] user's undo stack accumulates N EditLayerFieldCommands here
#[sub] and N reverses on the show_all. That's the documented chatty-
#[sub] for-undo property of these set verbs.
#[sub]
#[sub] Note: `hide_others` takes the target iid as its first arg.
#[sub] Variables substitute outside-quoted-strings, bounded by
#[sub] start/whitespace/`.`, so `hide_others a` substitutes the
#[sub] bound iid in cleanly.

layers hide_others a
assert layers.a visible == true
assert layers.b visible == false
assert layers.c visible == false

#[sub] show_all — reverse the previous. All test layers visible again.

layers show_all
assert layers.a visible == true
assert layers.b visible == true
assert layers.c visible == true

#[sub] move — reorder. We don't have iid-relative position queries
#[sub] yet, so the assert here is "the verb dispatched without error
#[sub] and the iid still resolves afterwards" (the layer didn't get
#[sub] lost in the reorder).

layers move a "top"
assert layers.a name == "smoke_test_a"
layers move a "bottom"
assert layers.a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] Deprecated-alias regression (s217 m2). The old verb names
#[sub] `set_color`, `set_opacity`, `make_active` still dispatch to
#[sub] the same code paths as their renamed counterparts. Existing
#[sub] scripts predating s217 m2 keep working unchanged. The aliases
#[sub] are NOT listed in `verbs()` (so new authors discover the
#[sub] canonical names from `list`-style introspection); they're
#[sub] purely behavioural compatibility. Scheduled for removal in
#[sub] s218+ once existing scripts have been swept.

layers.b set_color "#00ff00"
assert layers.b color == "#00ff00"
layers.b set_color ""

layers.c set_opacity 0.75
assert layers.c opacity == 0.75
layers.c set_opacity 1.0

layers.a make_active
get layers active_iid
set alias_active_a to result
assert layers.alias_active_a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] === Phase 3: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Delete every smoke_test_* layer using the bound variables.
#[sub] The keep-at-least-one-real-layer invariant means at least one
#[sub] of the original layers survives — but that's the user's, not
#[sub] ours, so we never touched it. After deletion, name queries on
#[sub] the bound variables would dispatch to dead iids — the router's
#[sub] proxy lookup fails because the iid is no longer in the model.
#[sub] We rely on the `delete` verb's own `ok` report rather than
#[sub] asserting post-delete state (which would unknown-object and
#[sub] increment the error count).

layers delete a
layers delete b
layers delete c

#[sub] Registry sanity — list at end, same as list at start of any
#[sub] previous m1-style run. `layers` remains; no `layers.<iid>`
#[sub] entries despite the dozens of transient proxies materialised
#[sub] across this run. Variables don't get registered either —
#[sub] they're listener-local, not registry entries.

list

#[sub] Done. Build-up created three test layers and bound each iid to
#[sub] a variable. Validate exercised every element verb and element
#[sub] query through `layers.<var>` addressing — no `find_by_name`
#[sub] wallpaper, no slot-refresh dance. Tear-down removed every
#[sub] smoke_test_* layer, returning the project to its pre-test state
#[sub] (minus undo-stack entries, which the user can clear via Edit
#[sub] menu if needed). The user's original layers were never
#[sub] addressed.
#[sub]
#[sub] Compare git history: this script went from ~300 lines of
#[sub] find_by_name wallpaper to ~210 lines of direct addressing.
#[sub] Every model Scriptable in 5a inherits this pattern.
